00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:12.119
Sorry, yeah. So zero-knowledge proof is basically a concept around cybersecurity where you can

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:18.760
validate stuff without actually knowing the actual answers. So I was just wondering if

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:25.079
there's any applications around personal data that help making working with easier, because, you know,

00:23:25.959 --> 00:23:31.560
I'm in Europe and GDPR is quite a big thing over here. And, you know, there's a lot of concerns

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:41.160
around privacy. Yeah. Are zero-knowledge proofs, is that like the same as homomorphic encryption,

00:23:41.160 --> 00:23:49.640
or is it like a concept around homomorphic encryption? Yeah, it's different. It's a

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:57.800
concept around how do we, so basically, you can prove to the other person that you know something

00:23:57.800 --> 00:24:06.040
without the other person actually knowing it. So, for example, if you have a key, you can prove to

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:10.040
the other person, I have this key, but the other person wouldn't know what the keys look like.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:19.640
Yeah, gotcha, gotcha. Yeah, so during, I can't speak too knowledgeably about this specific

00:24:19.640 --> 00:24:27.079
question. I do have some experience with like implementing privacy, privacy

00:24:29.239 --> 00:24:38.839
enhancing technologies in organizations. So at Immuta, we, the product would scan a data warehouse

00:24:38.839 --> 00:24:43.640
for sensitive data and tag it. So like it would say, all right, this looks like you have social

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:47.400
security numbers, it looks like you have addresses, it looks like you have names and things like that.

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:54.280
And then there were a couple of approaches that we could automatically implement if you had a policy

00:24:55.560 --> 00:25:04.199
that wanted to mitigate privacy concerns. The ones that we had were masking technology, masking

00:25:04.199 --> 00:25:13.079
methods, like hashing, redaction, replacement with string, rounding, etc. We had one that was

00:25:13.079 --> 00:25:19.800
called k-anonymization and we had one that was called differential privacy. So I think there's

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:28.920
a whole other set of methods like zero-knowledge proofs, homomorphic encryption. It's another one

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:34.680
I can't remember, but basically there's a number of technologies that you can implement.

00:25:35.719 --> 00:25:44.920
What I'll say is that it's for a lot of organizations, just implementing like the

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:53.400
basics is very, very, the basics at scale is very, very challenging because you have to have a lot of

00:25:53.800 --> 00:26:00.280
metadata, essentially, a lot of high-quality metadata to do privacy

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:09.160
management very, very well. So you have to know, you have to have a language around what

00:26:09.160 --> 00:26:17.239
is sensitive data, you have to have metadata on the data itself that says this column is

00:26:17.479 --> 00:26:23.319
sensitive. You have to have policies in place in your organization. So you have to know,

00:26:23.319 --> 00:26:29.959
like actually, you actually have to have someone who's translating that into an actionable policy

00:26:29.959 --> 00:26:34.040
of like, we need to mask this type of data for these types of users. You have to have high-quality

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:40.359
user data to know like who is accessible. And in Europe, you also have to have like this concept

00:26:40.359 --> 00:26:48.760
of projects and purposes around like what is, for this person using this data under these

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:53.000
parameters, like why are they using it? And you have to manage all of that in one place.

00:26:54.839 --> 00:26:59.079
So it's extremely challenging to get all those things right. I think what we found,

00:26:59.079 --> 00:27:03.959
like what we spent a lot of our time doing at Immuta was trying to help organizations build

00:27:03.959 --> 00:27:10.760
a language that would allow them to address those sorts of questions at scale, because I

00:27:10.760 --> 00:27:19.719
think that's really the problem. So all of that to say, I think what we found oftentimes was that

00:27:19.719 --> 00:27:23.319
people would come in and they'd say like, we want to do differential privacy, which is essentially

00:27:23.319 --> 00:27:30.280
like randomizing, injecting randomization into your data set to provide a level of privacy

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:36.119
guarantees. But then they'd always end up going down to like, let's just mask the data,

00:27:36.119 --> 00:27:42.280
like let's just mask the data and like get it, like get started using it rather than like trying

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:50.520
to do the most private thing first off. I think individual research teams, however, individual

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:55.880
teams that have like a very specific project they're trying to do, they can have a lot more

00:27:55.880 --> 00:28:00.359
success with things like differential privacy, homomorphic encryption, and that type of stuff.

00:28:00.359 --> 00:28:06.199
So there's probably a lot of value for certain use cases that are very well-defined,

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:14.599
you know. So that's kind of my, I don't know, my big picture thought on that.

00:28:14.599 --> 00:28:18.359
Yeah, I think that's definitely one of the masking, definitely one of the future

00:28:18.359 --> 00:28:23.880
of data as, you know, previously become more of an issue, because client wouldn't even let us

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:29.319
touch the data because it's too sensitive. And, you know, in Europe, you have to jump to sort of

00:28:29.319 --> 00:28:36.359
hoops to be able to work with personal data. Yeah, yeah. And it can be hard, like something

00:28:36.359 --> 00:28:45.079
like that can be very useful, you know, especially for like, there's different phases of

00:28:45.079 --> 00:28:49.479
analytics, right? So there's like just knowing that someone else's data could be useful to you,

00:28:49.479 --> 00:28:53.000
like that's where you want to have something like that zero-knowledge group where it's like, hey,

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:59.719
can we even start on this question? Because you might not have the data that you need

00:29:01.560 --> 00:29:06.599
to actually do anything meaningful with. And if you can't see it at all, you can't know

00:29:06.599 --> 00:29:13.079
whether it's worth pursuing. Arifat, I see you had clapped and then raised your hand.

