reading a book called Data Management at Scale. It's very, like, theoretical, but one of the

01:05:10.120 --> 01:05:18.760
principles is this idea of domain-driven design, which is as data comes in to your system,

01:05:19.719 --> 01:05:23.719
you don't want to build just, like, a big black box where it's, like, again, it's kind of

01:05:23.719 --> 01:05:28.760
explainability, right? So when data comes in from, you know, the marketing team and the sales team

01:05:28.760 --> 01:05:34.439
and the customer success team, you don't want to just, like, merge it into one, like, super, super,

01:05:35.080 --> 01:05:41.639
super table and then, like, expose it. You want to try and set up, like, interfaces where it's,

01:05:41.639 --> 01:05:45.879
like, all right, here's the lightly processed marketing data. Here's the lightly processed

01:05:45.879 --> 01:05:49.159
sales data. Here's the lightly processed customer success data and kind of keep some,

01:05:51.159 --> 01:05:56.919
keep some, you want to track the lineage, right? So that you know, like, hey, this is coming from

01:05:56.919 --> 01:06:03.159
here. And then if someone from marketing or sales or product comes in, they don't have to ask, like,

01:06:03.159 --> 01:06:06.840
where does this come from? Like, where's this marketing, you know, I'm looking at sales data,

01:06:06.840 --> 01:06:10.280
but I'm getting all this extra marketing data with it. What I found is that

01:06:13.639 --> 01:06:21.239
the more you can do that, the more people can, like, feel, feel ownership over it. I, we did

01:06:21.239 --> 01:06:26.439
this one thing at Immuta where we exposed Salesforce, which is our customer relationship

01:06:26.439 --> 01:06:31.320
management platform. It has, like, all of our customer lists and stuff in it. Salesforce data

01:06:31.320 --> 01:06:37.399
comes into the warehouse, then it gets exposed in our BI tool Looker. And there was this weird

01:06:37.399 --> 01:06:44.600
thing where the person who managed Salesforce would look at numbers in Looker and they would be,

01:06:44.600 --> 01:06:49.800
like, I don't know what these are. Like, they wouldn't, they didn't feel ownership over it

01:06:49.800 --> 01:06:55.800
simply because it was, like, going through our pipes. And so we re-architected things and

01:06:56.679 --> 01:07:05.959
tried to keep it much more, like, domain oriented. And they, that had the positive effect of, like,

01:07:05.959 --> 01:07:09.320
making them feel more ownership over it. Because they would go and they'd look at Looker and they'd

01:07:09.320 --> 01:07:12.840
look at Salesforce and be like, okay, this matches up. Like, and they kind of go and do that.

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:20.360
And that sort of building trust and building familiarity with the data is really hard.

01:07:21.320 --> 01:07:29.639
But I think it's easier if you can keep things separate and lightly processed and just have

01:07:29.639 --> 01:07:33.159
good documentation and clarity. But it's a challenge. I think it's probably one of the

01:07:33.159 --> 01:07:37.000
biggest challenges in data management. Thank you so much.

01:07:39.399 --> 01:07:45.080
Thank you so much, Stephen, for jumping on and sharing your experience with us. And thank you

01:07:45.159 --> 01:07:50.600
all for asking all these amazing questions, too. I just wanted to see, Stephen, what's the best way

